Cleaning and standardising — nulls, types, and casting.

These are really two jobs that run together on almost every silver build: first get rid of the bad nulls, then pin the real types.

Start with nulls. Three operations cover about ninety percent of what you'll do. Drop-n-a with a subset drops rows that are null in your required columns — transaction-i-d, customer-i-d, amount. Fill-n-a with a dictionary replaces nulls with a default — merchant category becomes "unknown", is-flagged becomes false. And for anything conditional, you reach for when and otherwise inside a with-column.

There's one drop-n-a detail the exam likes to test. The default, how equals "any", drops a row if any column is null. How equals "all" only drops a row when every single column is null. And you scope either one with the subset argument so you're only looking at the columns you care about.

Now standardising types. Bronze lands everything as a string on purpose — that way the schema-on-read step never loses data. Silver is where you pin the real types: cast amount to decimal eighteen-two, cast is-flagged to boolean, and run transaction-at through to-timestamp.

And here's the pitfall the exam absolutely loves. When a cast fails — a string that just won't parse — Spark does not raise an error. It silently produces a null. So you have to defend against it. Either land the bad rows in a quarantine table and alert when the row count climbs, or use try-cast in Spark S-Q-L, which does exactly the same thing as cast but makes that null-on-failure behaviour explicit and intentional.
